
1. Set up python environment
	a. Ensure you are using python 2 and not python 3
	b. Install pip through your OS
	c. Install virtualenv
	> pip install virtualenv
	d. Create a virtualenv for muckrock
	> virtualenv muckrock
	e. Activate the virtualenv
	> source muckrock/bin/activate
See more: http://docs.python-guide.org/en/latest/dev/virtualenvs/

2. Check out the repository from github:
	a. Create a github account and have us give you access to the muckrock repository
	b. Check out the repository
	> git clone git@github.com:MuckRock/muckrock.git
See more: https://help.github.com/articles/set-up-git#platform-all
http://git-scm.com/documentation

3. Install the requirements
	a. Go into the repository directory
	> cd muckrock
	b. Install requirements
	> pip install -r requirements.txt

4. Set up the database
	a. Install postgresql through your OS
	b. Configure the database for muckrock
	> sudo su - postgres
	> createdb muckrock
	> createuser muckrock
	> psql
	>> GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE muckrock TO muckrock;
	>> ALTER USER muckrock CREATEDB;
	ctrl+d to exit psql
	c. Ensure the database server is running

5. Set the secrets
	a. Create a file local_settings.py, which contains sensitive information that will not be checked into the repository
	b. We will send you the sensitive information in a secure manner

6. Sync the database
	a. Sync the db - create a superuser when it asks you to
	> ./manage.py syncdb
	b. Run the migrations
	> ./manage.py migrate

7. Run the test server
	a. Run the test server
	> ./manage.py runserver
	b. Navigate your web browser to http://127.0.0.1:8000


You should have a very bare MuckRock site running locally now.  Putting some documents into the database will help flesh out the site.

